t Lambert  as bishop of Maastricht and is regarded as the patron of hunters, since, like  St Eustace , he is supposed to have seen a vision of Christ crucified between the antlers of a stag."]},{"name":"Hugbert","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was popular among the Normans, who introduced it to Britain, where it was later reinforced by settlers from the Low Countries. An 8th-century  St Hubert  succeeded  St Lambert  as bishop of Maastricht and is regarded as the patron of hunters, since, like  St Eustace , he is supposed to have seen a vision of Christ crucified between the antlers of a stag."]}]},{"name":"fitz","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Either a short form of any of the numerous names representing a transferred use of a surname formed with the Anglo-Norman French prefix <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son of ’, as for example   Fitzgerald  ,   Fitzroy  , or a transferred use of the surname <i>Fitz</i>, which may be of the same derivation, but applied originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same given name, or a local name from Fitz in Shropshire, named with the Old English personal name <i>Fitt</i> + <i>hōh</i> ‘hill spur’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Ralph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralf","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Criche","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Clovis, Roch.","Altered form, under the French influence in LA, of German <b>Trischl</b>, a variant of <b>Drischel</b>, itself probably a derivative of <b>Driesch</b>, a topographic name from Middle Low German <i>drēsch</i>, <i>drīsch</i> ‘uncultivated land serving as pasture’, for someone who lived near such field. The surname <i>Triche</i> is also found among African Americans. In Germany, the original surname is today very rare (in both possible forms, <i>Trischl</i> and <i>Trischel</i>). Compare   Trichel  .","In some cases possibly also French: from Old French <i>triche</i> ‘trickery, deception’, or, written <b>Triché</b>, from the past participle of <i>tricher</i> ‘to trick or deceive’. Both surnames, which are very rare in France, may have denoted a cheat or a cunning, deceitful person."],"variants":[{"name":"Tricot","meanings":["(2010: NA)","French:","nickname from a diminutive of <i>trique</i> ‘cudgel’."]},{"name":"Trichell","meanings":["Altered form, under the French influence in LA, of German <b>Trischl</b> (see   Triche   1)."]},{"name":"Trichel","meanings":["Altered form, under the French influence in LA, of German <b>Trischl</b> (see   Triche   1)."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Hubert fitz Ralph of Criche was born about 1195, in Crich, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom. He married Edelina FitzWilliam before 1220, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters."},"et":{"about 1195–":"umbes 1195–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1220–Female":"1220–Surnud","1222–Female":"1222–Surnud","1195–Male":"1195–Surnud","about 1195":"umbes 119